	<title>Examples: Area of a Parallelogram Using Cross Products</title>
	<caption>Examples: Parallelogram Area</caption>
	
	
	
	<example>
		<statement>
			<para>Find the area of the parallelogram in <latex>\RNr[3]</latex> spanned by the vectors</para>
			<para align="center"><latex>\Vect{x} = (1,1,-2)</latex> &nbsp; and &nbsp; <latex>\Vect{y} = (-3,-1,1)</latex></para>
		</statement>
		
		<answer type="Solution">
			<para>We use the fact that <latex>\abs{ \CrssPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} } }</latex> is the area of the parallelogram spanned by <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>. We find:</para>
			<computation>
				<left>\CrssPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} }</left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>(-1,5,2)</right>
			</computation>
			<para>Therefore the area of the given parallelogram is</para>
			<computation>
				<left>\abs{ (-1,5,2) }</left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>\sqrt{ 30 }</right>
			</computation>
		</answer>
	</example>
	
	
	
	
	<example>
		<statement>
			<para>Find the area of the triangle in <latex>\RNr[3]</latex> with vertices</para>
			<para align="center"><latex>(2,-1,3)</latex>, &nbsp; <latex>(1,2,-2)</latex>, and &nbsp; <latex>(-1,1,1)</latex>.</para>
		</statement>
		<answer type="Solution">
			<para>The vectors joining <latex>(1,2,-2)</latex> to the points <latex>(2,-1,3)</latex> and <latex>(-1,1,1)</latex>, respectively, are given by</para>
			<computation>
				<left>\Vect{x}</left>
				<center>:=</center>
				<right>(2,-1,3) - (1,2,-2) = (1,-3,5)</right>
				<left>\Vect{y}</left>
				<center>:=</center>
				<right>(-1,1,1) - (1,2,-2) = (-2,-1,3)</right>
			</computation>
			<para>The area of the given triangle is half the area of the parallelogram spanned by <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>. Therefore the area of the triangle is</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>\frac{1}{2}\cdot \abs{ \CrssPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} } } = \frac{1}{2}\cdot \abs{ (-4,-13,-7) } = \frac{1}{2}\cdot \sqrt{ 234 }</latex>
			</math.display>
			
		</answer>
	</example>
	
